external_knowledge:
- "storm of unresolved issues" refers to the collection of errors needing attention;
- "turbulent error instances" metaphorically describes error instances that are problematic and require immediate action;
- "storm type" refers to the type of error, such as business or technical;
- "intensity" refers to the severity of the error, measured as low, medium, or high;
- "tossed to the winds" metaphorically indicates the errors that have been processed by a specific user but remain unresolved, in this case, by 'John Doe';
- "awaiting the next wave of escalation" refers to errors with a 'resolution_status' of 'escalation_required'.

sql:
SELECT category, COUNT(error_type_id) AS error_type_count
FROM error_types
GROUP BY category;

SELECT DISTINCT users.user_id, users.role 
FROM users 
JOIN error_comments ON users.user_id = error_comments.user_id;

SELECT COUNT(*) AS TotalErrors
FROM error_reports
WHERE report_data LIKE '%technical%';

SELECT error_comments.error_instance_id, error_comments.comment_date, error_comments.comment_text
FROM error_comments
WHERE error_comments.comment_text LIKE '%pending%';

SELECT transaction_id, COUNT(error_instance_id) AS error_count
FROM error_instances
GROUP BY transaction_id;

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT transaction_id) AS total_transactions_with_errors
FROM error_instances
WHERE error_date BETWEEN '2022-01-01' AND '2022-12-31';

